The paper discusses the use of central pattern generators (CPGs) for legged locomotion control, which is a common topic in robotics (cs.RO). The learning mechanism used in the paper is based on a simulated annealing algorithm, which falls under the category of neural networks (cs.NE). The paper also deals with adaptive locomotion generation, which involves the coordination of multiple body parts, making it relevant to the systems and control (cs.SY) and artificial intelligence (cs.AI) sub-categories. Finally, the paper evaluates the performance of the system using experimental results, which falls under the category of machine learning (cs.LG).
